It has been seen that the chemical potential for carrier g-C3N4 is lesser i.e., −4.653 eV than that of levosimendan (−4.997 eV) and g-C3N4-levosimendan (−4.89 eV). Chemical potential values signify the electron transfer from occupied to unoccupied orbitals (Fig. 4
                        ). Chemical softness for the complex of g-C3N4-levosimendan is greater (0.325 eV) than both the g-C3N4 and levosimendan while the hardness value for g-C3N4-levosimenda n is lesser i.e., 3.076 than the rest of fragments as shown from Table 3 and Fig. 5
                        . These results indicate that the complex is softer than its individual components signifying more better reactivity while the lower hardness value confirms that the complex has better drug-donor inter-actions with lower resistance. The dipole moment calculated for complex g-C3N4-levosimendan (5.56 D) is greater than that of g-C3N4 (1.58 D). This increase in dipole moment describes the increased solubility factor. It has been seen that with the adsorption of drug on carrier; µ, η and energy gap show decreased values suggesting lesser stability and more activity of the complex. While electrophilicity index shows that energy reduction take place for g-C3N4-levosimendan as surrounding charges are not effective. Thus, all these parameters are in favor of the complex and g-C3N4 offers a good route of administration for cardiovascular drugs. In solvent phase the same parameters are evaluated, and the results are shown in Table 4. Dipole moment for g-C3N4, levosimendan and their complex are increased in solvent phase but the thing to be noted is that the dipole moment shows a significant increase for complex i.e., 9.52 D which means that it has high solubility in water as compared to that of gas phase (Fig. 6
                        ).
